<p>
  If there's one piece of advice that applies to nearly every kind of speech, vow, or letter, it's
  this: a specific story will almost always move people more than a general statement, no matter
  how sincere that statement is.
</p>

<h2>Why stories work when adjectives don't</h2>
<p>
  Telling someone "you're the kindest person I know" states a conclusion. Telling them about the
  time they drove two hours in bad weather to sit with a friend in the hospital lets the listener
  reach that conclusion themselves — and conclusions people reach on their own tend to land harder
  than ones they're simply told. A good story does the convincing so you don't have to state the
  point outright.
</p>

<h2>The story doesn't need to be dramatic</h2>
<p>
  There's a common assumption that a meaningful story needs to be a big, obvious moment — a grand
  gesture, a dramatic turning point. In practice, small, ordinary stories often carry just as much
  weight, sometimes more, because they feel true rather than performed. The way someone answers
  the phone, a specific joke they always make, a small routine only you would notice — these can be
  more revealing than any single dramatic event.
</p>

<h2>How to find your story</h2>
<p>
  If you're stuck trying to think of "the" story, try a different question: what's a moment you
  find yourself bringing up naturally, in conversation, without trying? The stories you already
  tell — the ones that come up at dinner, in a group chat, in a toast at a smaller gathering — are
  usually the ones worth building on, because they're already proven to resonate with the people who
  know this person.
</p>
<blockquote>
  You already have the feelings. We simply help you express them.
</blockquote>

<h2>Let the detail do the work</h2>
<p>
  Once you have a story, resist the urge to explain its meaning afterward. If you tell the story
  well, with a specific enough detail, you often don't need to add "and that's when I knew" — the
  room will already understand. Trust the story to carry the point rather than over-explaining it.
</p>

<h2>One story, chosen well, is enough</h2>
<p>
  You don't need five examples to prove a point about someone. One well-chosen, specific story,
  given room to breathe, usually says more than a longer list ever could. This is, in a lot of
  ways, the whole idea behind how we approach every project — listening for the one detail that
  makes a piece unmistakably about a specific person, rather than reaching for something that could
  apply to anyone.
</p>
